SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR
$SOL
$BR
One can compute \(f'\) using the product rule, but it is easier to re-write $BR
\( f(x)=\{$f->reduce->TeX\}=x^2-$c x^{3/2}\)$BR
Then \(f'(x)=2x-$c\cdot \frac{3}{2}x^{1/2}\) and \(f''(x)=2-$c\cdot \frac{3}{4}x^{-1/2}=2-\frac{$c\cdot 3}{4\sqrt{x}}\).
$PAR
Now, \(f\) is $int1_concave for \(0 < x < $cp\) since \(f''(x) $int1_fsign\) there.  Moreover, \(f\) is $int2_concave for \(x > $cp\) since \(f''(x) $int2_fsign\) there.  

Finally, because \(f''(x)\) changes sign at \(x = $cp\), \(f(x)\) has a point of inflection at \(x = 9\).
END_SOLUTION

